Justification: Despite a history of appendectomy, appendicitis is a common cause of lower abdominal pain and should be considered, although less likely due to surgical history.
The patient is a young female with lower abdominal pain and cramping, which could indicate an ovarian cyst issue, especially given the acute onset.
Although the patient is on birth control, no contraceptive method is 100% effective. The acute onset of lower abdominal pain in a sexually active female warrants consideration of ectopic pregnancy.
The patient is sexually active, and PID can present with lower abdominal pain and nausea.
Although there is no diarrhea, gastroenteritis can present with cramping abdominal pain and nausea.
UTI is less likely due to the absence of urinary symptoms, but it can sometimes present atypically.
The timing of the pain, two weeks after the last menstrual period, could correspond with ovulation pain, known as Mittelschmerz.
